"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1129494","Department for Education","false","2019-06-18","<p>The independent panel’s report forms an important step in the government’s Review of Post-18 Education and Funding. The government will consider the panel’s recommendations carefully and engage with stakeholders before concluding the review at the Spending Review.</p><p> </p><p>The Adult Education Budget aims to provide adults with the skills and learning that they need to equip them for work, an apprenticeship or other learning. It enables flexible tailored programmes, which may or may not require a qualification, to be made available to help eligible adults to undertake in learning programmes, build their confidence and enhance their wellbeing. This includes community learning and funding to help learners overcome barriers to learning, such as financial hardship or learning difficulties or disabilities. The department is considering adult skills more widely in preparation for the upcoming Spending Review.</p><p> </p>",,"Lord Agnew of Oulton","HL15977 ; HL15978 ; HL15980","2019-06-18T13:16:01.853Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1129494/answer","Biography information for Lord Agnew of Oulton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1129494/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1129494/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2019-06-04","Adult Education","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government what support they (1) make, and (2) plan to make, available to adult learners who wish to study without the intention of obtaining a qualification.","false","Biography information for Lord Bird",,"Lord Bird","HL15979"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1129495","Department for Education","false","2019-06-18","<p>The independent panel’s report forms an important step in the government’s Review of Post-18 Education and Funding. The government will consider the panel’s recommendations carefully and engage with stakeholders before concluding the review at the Spending Review.</p><p> </p><p>The Adult Education Budget aims to provide adults with the skills and learning that they need to equip them for work, an apprenticeship or other learning. It enables flexible tailored programmes, which may or may not require a qualification, to be made available to help eligible adults to undertake in learning programmes, build their confidence and enhance their wellbeing. This includes community learning and funding to help learners overcome barriers to learning, such as financial hardship or learning difficulties or disabilities. The department is considering adult skills more widely in preparation for the upcoming Spending Review.</p><p> </p>",,"Lord Agnew of Oulton","HL15977 ; HL15978 ; HL15979","2019-06-18T13:16:01.9Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1129495/answer","Biography information for Lord Agnew of Oulton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1129495/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1129495/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2019-06-04","Education: Disadvantaged","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government what is their strategy to reduce inequality in education; and how any strategy will include adult community learning providers who already provide support to disadvantaged and vulnerable communities.","false","Biography information for Lord Bird",,"Lord Bird","HL15980"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1129496","Department for Transport","false","2019-06-17","<p>The Office of Rail and Road (ORR) publishes data on the electrified rail route operated by Network Rail in Great Britain. This includes routes open to passengers and freight and does not contain a breakdown for passengers only.</p><p>The length of Network Rail operated electrified route in Great Britain (so excluding the High Speed 1 line, for example) was 3,583 miles in 2017-18. This represents 36% of the total Network Rail mainline railway route.</p><p>This data is available at the following link:</p><p><a href="https://dataportal.orr.gov.uk/displayreport/report/html/c35e0c28-324f-4168-81b9-be197963f251" target="_blank">https://dataportal.orr.gov.uk/displayreport/report/html/c35e0c28-324f-4168-81b9-be197963f251</a></p>",,"Baroness Vere of Norbiton",,"2019-06-17T15:39:54.633Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1129496/answer","Biography information for Baroness Vere of Norbiton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1129496/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1129496/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2019-06-04","Railways: Electrification","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government what percentage of rail passenger miles are powered by electricity.","false","Biography information for Lord Birt",,"Lord Birt","HL15981"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1129497","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2019-06-12","<p>The smart meter rollout in Great Britain is making good progress, with over 14.3 million smart and advanced meters operating as of the end of March 2019. The Programme remains on track to offer every home and small business smart meters by the end of 2020.</p>",,"Lord Henley",,"2019-06-12T15:11:47.82Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1129497/answer","Biography information for Lord Henley","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1129497/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1129497/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2019-06-04","Energy: Meters","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government whether the target for energy suppliers to have taken all reasonable steps to install smart meters in all homes and small businesses in the UK will be met by 2020.","false","Biography information for Lord Birt",,"Lord Birt","HL15982"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1129498","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2019-06-18","<p>UK expenditure on energy including imports was approximately £150bn (including taxes) or £113bn (excluding taxes, duties and levies) in 2017[1]. As a direct share, this is 5-7% of GDP depending on the inclusion of taxes, duties and levies. The Government is working to continue to improve energy efficiency across the economy in order to deliver affordable, clean and secure energy – the amount of energy used per unit of GDP has already fallen by 49% since 1990, and we are independently assessed as leading the G20 in cutting emissions while growing the economy since 2000. Our ambitious plans and policies to mitigate against the threat of climate change are set out in the Clean Growth Strategy.</p><p> </p><p>The Government publishes projections of the future volume of energy use based on current and planned policies under a range of sensitivities from now to 2035. The most recent projections can be found on Gov.uk.</p><p>[1] Table 1.4 Digest of UK Energy Statistics (copy attached)</p>",,"Lord Henley",,"2019-06-18T14:32:50.037Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1129498/answer","Biography information for Lord Henley","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1129498/answer","Table 1.4 Digest of UK Energy Statistics.xls","Table 1.4 Digest of UK Energy Statistics.xls","able 1.4 Digest of UK Energy Statistics","able 1.4 Digest of UK Energy Statistics","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1129498/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2019-06-04","Energy","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government what percentage of GDP is represented by energy use; and what proportion of GDP is estimated to be represented by energy use by (1) 2030, (2) 2040, and (3) 2050, if their current climate change policies are enacted.","false","Biography information for Lord Birt",,"Lord Birt","HL15